Introduction to the scalpel R Package

Ashley Petersen

2017-03-13

This will guide you through using the scalpel package to extract neurons from calcium imaging data. Throughout this guide, youll see gray boxes that contain a mix of R comments (lines beginning with #), R commands, and R output (lines beginning with #>). We demonstrate how to use the package with a small simulated data set (500 frames with each frame having 30 x 30 pixels) that is included in the R package itself. Thus, feel free to run the code yourself and check that your results match those presented here. To easily follow along, you can us the R script SCALPELvignette_code.R (available at ajpete.com/software) that includes all of the commands run in this vignette. Note that there are a few chunks of code that were not run as part of this vignette. These include the comment ###NOT RUN at the beginning of their chunks in this vignette and are commented out in SCALPELvignette_code.R.

For complete documentation of all of the functions in this package, please see the reference manual, which is available at https://CRAN.R-project.org/package=scalpel/scalpel.pdf. Alternatively, you can access the documentation for a specific function in R using the command ?function. For example, use ?scalpelStep3 to find out more about the scalpelStep3() function.

First, we load the scalpel package, along with the Matrix package, which well need later.

library(scalpel)
library(Matrix)

Quick Start Guide

In this section, well illustrate how easy it is to run SCALPEL using the default parameters on the simulated data set included with the R package. We can run the entire SCALPEL pipeline using scalpel(). There are several arguments for this function, however, all but three of the arguments have default values that are used if the argument is not specified. For now, we will rely on the default values, and only specify the necessary arguments: where the raw data we want to analyze is saved (rawDataFolder), the height of the video we are analyzing (videoHeight), and where the results should be saved (outputFolder). Later, we will revisit how to run the pipeline with non-default parameters. Status messages are printed out while the pipeline is running, which can be helpful when processing larger videos.

#example video is provided with the R package
#automatically locate the folder that contains "Y_1.rds"
rawDataFolder = gsub("Y_1.rds", "", system.file("extdata", "Y_1.rds", package = "scalpel"))
#define the height of the example video
videoHeight = 30
#existing folder in which to save various results
#if rerunning this code yourself, change this to an existing folder on your computer
outputFolder = "~/Desktop/miniData/"

#run the entire SCALPEL pipeline
miniOut = scalpel(outputFolder = outputFolder, videoHeight = videoHeight, rawDataFolder = rawDataFolder)
#> Beginning Step 0 of SCALPEL

#> Performing segmentation for threshold 2 of 3

Now that weve run the entire SCALPEL pipeline, we can take a look at the results. To display a map of the neurons found and their estimated calcium concentrations over time, use plotResults().

plotResults(scalpelOutput = miniOut)

As a reminder, there are three different dictionaries at different steps of the SCALPEL pipeline. After Step 1, we have the preliminary dictionary, saved as miniOut$Azero. After Step 2, we have the refined dictionary, saved as miniOut$A. And finally, after Step 3, we have the filtered dictionary, saved as miniOut$Afilter.

#the dimensions of the dictionaries: (number of pixels) x (number of elements)
dim(miniOut$Azero)
#> [1] 900 468
dim(miniOut$A)
#> [1] 900   3
dim(miniOut$Afilter)
#> [1] 900   3

In this example, the refined and filtered dictionaries have the same number of elements, but this isnt always the case. In a later section, well show an example of when this isnt true.

To compare these neurons we found to a summary of the video data, we use plotVideoVariance(), which displays a heat map of the variance at each pixel with the identified neurons outlined. The brightest white pixels have the highest variance across the frames, and a group of neighboring pixels with high variance is likely to be a neuron. We specify neuronSet = "Afilter" to indicate that we want to outline the filtered dictionary from Step 3, instead of using neuronSet = "A" to outline the dictionary from Step 2.

plotVideoVariance(scalpelOutput = miniOut, neuronSet = "Afilter")

For further evidence of whether or not the neurons we identified are likely real, we can examine the frames in which the neurons were estimated to have the largest calcium concentrations. The AfilterIndex argument allows us to specify the neuron (i.e., column of miniOut$Afilter) in which we are interested.

#show the brightest frame for each estimated neuron
plotBrightest(scalpelOutput = miniOut, AfilterIndex = 1)
plotBrightest(scalpelOutput = miniOut, AfilterIndex = 2)
plotBrightest(scalpelOutput = miniOut, AfilterIndex = 3)

Lastly, we can gather more evidence as to whether an estimated neuron appears to be real using plotCandidateFrame(). This function plots an element from the cluster of a specified dictionary element, along with the frame of the video from which the element was derived.

#examine the 50th member of the cluster corresponding
#to the first element of the filtered dictionary, scalpelOutput$Afilter
plotCandidateFrame(scalpelOutput = miniOut, AfilterIndex = 1, member = 50)
#> There 172 members in the requested cluster. Member 99 is the representative for the cluster.

#examine the representative component of the cluster
plotCandidateFrame(scalpelOutput = miniOut, AfilterIndex = 1, member = 99)
#> There 172 members in the requested cluster. Member 99 is the representative for the cluster.

Rerunning Steps with Alternative Parameters

In addition to running the SCALPEL pipeline using scalpel(), the individual SCALPEL steps can be run using scalpelStep0(), scalpelStep1(), scalpelStep2(), and scalpelStep3(). There are various reasons that these functions may be helpful:

  • After running the entire pipeline, you may want to rerun one of the steps with alternative parameters. For example, if we wish to update the parameters for Step 3, we can call scalpelStep3() on the scalpel() output, instead of rerunning the entire pipeline, which can be time-intensive.

  • For large videos, the individual steps will be time consuming to run. Thus you may want to not run all of the steps at once.

  • You may want to review the results after each step before running the next step.

We illustrate these individual step functions in the sections below.

A Detailed Look at Step 0

This step involves data pre-processing. We read in the raw data and perform standard pre-processing techniques in order to smooth the data both temporally and spatially, remove the bleaching effect, and calculate a standardized fluorescence.

To run this step, you specify the parameters that we used above when calling scalpel() (outputFolder, rawDataFolder, and videoHeight), as well as possibly fileType. The fileType is either "R" (the default that we used above), "text", "zippedText", or "matlab". Because there arent any user-defined parameters that should change for the same video, this step should only be run once (either as part of scalpel() or using scalpelStep0()). Instead of running scalpel(), we could have used the following command to run Step 0: step0out = scalpelStep0(outputFolder = outputFolder, videoHeight = videoHeight, rawDataFolder = rawDataFolder).

Format of the Raw Data

In order for Step 0 to run properly, the raw data must be saved in a very specific way. The data should be a \(P \times T\) matrix, where \(P\) is the total number of pixels per image frame and \(T\) the number of frames of the video, for which the \((i,j)\)th element contains the fluorescence of the \(i\)th pixel in the \(j\)th frame. To create this matrix, you should vectorize each 2-dimensional image frame by concatenating the columns of the image frame. If the data is saved in a single file, it should be named Y_1.mat,Y_1.rds, Y_1.txt, or Y_1.txt.gz (depending on fileType), and if the data is split over multiple files, they should be split into chunks of the columns and named consecutively (Y_1.mat, Y_2.mat, etc.; Y_1.rds, Y_2.rds, etc.; Y_1.txt, Y_2.txt, etc.; or Y_1.txt.gz, Y_2.txt.gz, etc.).

If youve read your video data into R and the \(P\times T\) matrix is named Y, you can save it in the necessary format using saveRDS(Y, paste0(rawDataFolder, "Y_1.rds")), where rawDataFolder is an existing folder in which you want to save the raw data. If you want to split the raw data into multiple files containing e.g., 1000 frames each, this can be done using saveRDS(Y[,1:1000], paste0(rawDataFolder, "Y_1.rds")), saveRDS(Y[,1001:2000], paste0(rawDataFolder, "Y_2.rds")), etc.

Plotting Functions

There are three plotting functions that can be used with the output from scalpelStep0(): plotFrame(), plotThresholdedFrame(), and plotVideoVariance(). With plotFrame(), we can plot a specified frame of the raw video, or the processed video that results from Step 0. In all of our plotting functions, we will need to specify scalpelOutput, which is the output from scalpel() or the output from the corresponding step, which is scalpelStep0() for plotFrame(). In addition, we specify the frame number we wish to display. Note that the processed data is displayed by default, but that the raw data can instead be plotted using the videoType parameter. We also illustrate the shrinkLargest argument, which allows you to better visualize areas with high fluorescence as all values above shrinkCutoff are shrunk. We use the default value of shrinkCutoff. Note that shrinkLargest is an argument for all functions involving plotting frames of the video: plotThresholdedFrame(), plotVideoVariance(), plotCandidateFrame(), and plotBrightest().

#simplest example with default parameters
plotFrame(scalpelOutput = miniOut, frame = 100)
#using shrinkLargest argument
plotFrame(scalpelOutput = miniOut, frame = 100, shrinkLargest = TRUE)
#now plot the raw data instead of processed, and add a custom title
plotFrame(scalpelOutput = miniOut, frame = 100, videoType = "raw", title = "Raw Data for Frame 100")

As mentioned above, if we had instead run the SCALPEL pipeline step by step, we can also use plotFrame() on the output from calling scalpelStep0().

#run Step 0 using a different output folder
#to demonstrate plotting using output from scalpelStep0
step0out = scalpelStep0(outputFolder = "~/Desktop/miniDataVersion2/", videoHeight = videoHeight, rawDataFolder = rawDataFolder)
#> Beginning Step 0 of SCALPEL
#> Found 1 raw data files
#> Performing processing on part 1 of 1
#> Reading in raw data
#> Y has 900 total pixels and 500 frames
#> Performing temporal and spatial smoothing
#> Frame 100 of 500
#> Frame 200 of 500
#> Frame 300 of 500
#> Frame 400 of 500
#> Frame 500 of 500
#> Adjusting for possible bleaching effect
#> Performing 'delta f over f' transformation
#> Step 0 of SCALPEL finished!
#plot the same plot as above using output from scalpelStep0
plotFrame(scalpelOutput = step0out, frame = 100)

Plotting using plotThresholdedFrame() is very similar to plotFrame(), except we specify threshold and all pixels above that value are shaded. This is useful in deciding on the threshold values to use for image segmentation in Step 1, if you decide to forgo using the default values. In the plots below, we use the actual thresholds used in Step 1, which are saved in miniOut$thresholdVec.

#simplest example with default parameters
plotThresholdedFrame(scalpelOutput = miniOut, frame = 100, threshold = miniOut$thresholdVec[1])
#change shading to purple, add a title, and use a different threshold
plotThresholdedFrame(scalpelOutput = miniOut, frame = 100, col = "purple", threshold = miniOut$thresholdVec[2], title = "2nd Threshold Value")

The function updateThreshold() can be used to review and update the chosen threshold for image segmentation in Step 1. This is an optional step between Steps 0 and 1. Running the command, step0out = updateThreshold(step0Output = step0out), will start an interactive process to update the threshold.

We saw an example of how to use plotVideoVariance() above. Note that if scalpelOutput is the output from scalpelStep0(), not scalpel(), then neuronsToOutline will be ignored and the neurons will not be outlined (as they havent been identified yet).

#plot the raw data and add a title
plotVideoVariance(scalpelOutput = step0out, videoType = "raw", title = "Variance of Raw Data")
#> Warning in plotVideoVariance(scalpelOutput = step0out, videoType = "raw", :
#> Given the class of 'scalpelOutput', the neurons will not be outlined.
#we can choose whether to outline the neurons for object from scalpel() function
#when outlining neurons, also need to choose whether to plot neurons from dictionary from Step 2 (miniOut$A) or Step 3 (miniOut$Afilter)
plotVideoVariance(scalpelOutput = miniOut, neuronSet = "Afilter", neuronsToOutline = "all")
plotVideoVariance(scalpelOutput = miniOut, neuronsToOutline = "none")

A Detailed Look at Step 1

This step involves constructing a spatial component dictionary. We apply an image segmentation procedure to each frame of the video in order to derive a dictionary of preliminary dictionary elements. We hope that this dictionary will be a superset of the true neurons.

The arguments for this step pertain to the allowable size (in pixels) of the preliminary dictionary elements (minSize, maxSize, maxWidth, and maxHeight), as well as the threshold values (thresholdVec) to use in image segmentation. If thresholdVec is not specified, the default is to use the negative of the minimum of the processed data, the negative of the 0.1% quantile of the processed data, and the mean of these. When we ran scalpel() originally, we used these default values.

miniOut$thresholdVec
#> [1] 0.04658673 0.06364724 0.08070775

We can rerun Step 1 with alternative parameters, and look at the results using summary().

#use a larger minimum size, smaller maximum size, and smaller maximum width/height
#use two user-selected threshold values for image segmentation
step1out = scalpelStep1(step0Output = miniOut, minSize = 40, maxSize = 200, maxWidth = 20, maxHeight = 20, thresholdVec = c(0.05, 0.07))
#> Beginning Step 1 of SCALPEL
#> Performing image segmentation on part 1 of 1
#> Performing segmentation for threshold 1 of 2
#> Segmenting frame 100 of 158 bright frames
#> Performing segmentation for threshold 2 of 2
#> Segmenting frame 100 of 144 bright frames
#> Saving data needed in Step 2 of SCALPEL
#> Step 1 of SCALPEL finished!
#we can summarize the results
summary(step1out)
#> Step 1 of SCALPEL
#> 
#> SUMMARY
#> We performed image segmentation to produce a total of 291 preliminary dictionary elements, which came from 150 different frames of the video. There are 549 pixels contained in at least one preliminary dictionary element. The version (i.e., unique identifier) for this run of Step 1 is 87671.
#> 
#> ARGUMENTS USED
#> Minimum size of preliminary dictionary element allowed (in pixels): 40
#> Maximum size of preliminary dictionary element allowed (in pixels): 200
#> Maximum width of preliminary dictionary element allowed (in pixels): 20
#> Maximum height of preliminary dictionary element allowed (in pixels): 20
#> Threshold values used for image segmentation: 
#> 0.05
#> 0.07

Plotting Functions

The plotting function plotCandidateFrame() can be used with the output from scalpelStep1(). This function plots a specified preliminary dictionary element, along with the frame of the video from which the element was derived. This allows you to see if reasonable preliminary dictionary elements are being derived using the current threshold values. To choose which preliminary dictionary element we want to examine, we specify AzeroIndex, which is just the column of scalpelOutput$Azero that is of interest.

#simplest example with default parameters
plotCandidateFrame(scalpelOutput = miniOut, AzeroIndex = 10)

#plot raw data instead of processed, look at results from second run of Step 1
plotCandidateFrame(scalpelOutput = step1out, AzeroIndex = 50, videoType = "raw")

In addition to examining preliminary dictionary elements through directly specifying their column index using AzeroIndex, we can also choose an element of the refined dictionary from Step 2 (scalpelOutput$A) using the argument AIndex, or an element of the filtered dictionary from Step 3 (scalpelOutput$Afilter) using AfilterIndex. Recall that elements from both of these dictionaries correspond to an entire cluster of preliminary dictionary elements, thus we must also choose which cluster member to examine using the member argument.

#examine the 100th member of the cluster corresponding 
#to the third element of the refined dictionary, scalpelOutput$A
plotCandidateFrame(scalpelOutput = miniOut, AIndex = 3, member = 100)
#> There 249 members in the requested cluster. Member 245 is the representative for the cluster.

#if we choose 'member' to be larger than the cluster size, we'll get an error
plotCandidateFrame(scalpelOutput = miniOut, AIndex = 3, member = 300)
#> Error in plotCandidateFrame(scalpelOutput = miniOut, AIndex = 3, member = 300): Specify 'member' to be an integer in 1 to 249
#now examine the 25th member of the cluster corresponding
#to the second element of the filtered dictionary, scalpelOutput$Afilter
plotCandidateFrame(scalpelOutput = miniOut, AfilterIndex = 2, member = 25)
#> There 47 members in the requested cluster. Member 43 is the representative for the cluster.

A Detailed Look at Step 2

This step involves refinement of the spatial component dictionary from Step 1. We eliminate redundancy in the spatial component dictionary by clustering together preliminary dictionary elements that represent the same neuron, based on spatial and temporal information.

The arguments for this step are the cut-off value for the dendrogram (cutoff) and the dissimilarity weight \(\omega\) (omega). We recommend using the default value of 0.2 for omega. The default cutoff is 0.18. A smaller value will encourage a larger number of clusters, i.e., dictionary elements, and a larger value will encourage a smaller number of clusters.

We can rerun Step 2 with a smaller cutoff, and look at the results using summary().

step2out = scalpelStep2(step1Output = miniOut, cutoff = 0.08)
#> Beginning Step 2 of SCALPEL
#> Determining sets of overlapping preliminary dictionary elements
#> Clustering overlapping set: 1 of 2
#> Finding clusters
#> Clustering overlapping set: 2 of 2
#> Finding clusters
#> Step 2 of SCALPEL finished!
#we can summarize the results
summary(step2out)
#> Step 2 of SCALPEL
#> 
#> SUMMARY
#> We performed clustering on the 468 preliminary dictionary elements, which resulted in 5 dictionary elements.
#> 
#> ARGUMENTS USED
#> Cutoff for dendrogram: 0.08
#> Dissimilarity metric weight: 0.2
#> Maximum number of preliminary dictionary elements to cluster at once: 3000
#> 
#> ADVANCED USER INFO
#> There were 2 overlapping sets of components with the largest set containing 296 preliminary dictionary elements. The clustering shortcut for large sets of overlapping components was used. There were 0 overlapping sets for which the shortcut was used.

Now, instead of finding three dictionary elements, there are five! We visualize the difference in dictionary elements below.

Plotting Functions

There are two plotting functions useful in Step 2 of SCALPEL: plotSpatial() and plotCluster(). With plotSpatial(), we can compare the dictionary elements (which are saved as A in the output object) from our previous analysis that used 0.18 for cutoff to our current analysis using 0.08.

#the dictionary elements for cutoff=0.18
plotSpatial(scalpelOutput = miniOut, neuronSet = "A", title = paste0("Cutoff = ", miniOut$cutoff))
#the dictionary elements for cutoff=0.08
plotSpatial(scalpelOutput = step2out, neuronSet = "A", title = paste0("Cutoff = ", step2out$cutoff))

We can see that using too small of a value for cutoff leads to having multiple clusters that correspond to the same neuron (e.g., components 3-5 in the plot above).

We can visualize the preliminary dictionary elements in each cluster using plotCluster(). The AIndex argument specifies which dictionary elements cluster to visualize, where the numbering coincides with the columns of scalpelOutput$A.

On the left, we show the dictionary element of interest in orange, with the other dictionary elements in blue. In the middle, we transparently plot all of the preliminary dictionary elements corresponding to the component. On the right, we show the component in orange, along with the union of all of the preliminary dictionary elements in gray. Note that the plots in the middle and on the right are zoomed-in, compared to the plot on the left that shows the entire field of view for the video.

plotCluster(scalpelOutput = miniOut, AIndex = 1)

Note that we can also use the output from scalpelStep3() with plotCluster(). When we do this, we use the argument AfilterIndex to pick the cluster of interest, instead of AIndex. This index corresponds to columns of scalpelOutput$Afilter.

A Detailed Look at Step 3

This step involves spatial component selection and temporal component estimation. We estimate the temporal components corresponding to the dictionary elements by solving a sparse group lasso problem with a non-negativity constraint. Specifically, we minimize the following over Z with all non-negative elements:

0.5*sum((Y - AfilterTilde %*% Z)^2) + lambda*alpha*sum(Z) + lambda*(1-alpha)*sum(sqrt(rowSums(Z^2))),

where AfilterTilde is a scaled version of Afilter. Recall that Afilter is the filtered spatial component dictionary, which contains a subset of the columns of A from Step 2.

There are a few arguments in this step that pertain to which dictionary elements to include in Afilter. For example, the argument minClusterSize allows you to specify the minimum number of preliminary dictionary elements that a cluster must contain in order to be included in Afilter. The default value is 1, which minimizes the chance of erroneously excluding a true neuron. Using a larger value (e.g., 5) for minClusterSize will reduce the possibility of including components that are truly noise, while increasing the chance that we exclude a true neuron. In our example data, all three of the components have large cluster sizes, so for illustrative purposes, we choose a minClusterSize of 50. In practice, you should choose this parameter to be much smaller.

#require elements to have at least 50 members in their clusters
step3largeCluster = scalpelStep3(step2Output = miniOut, minClusterSize = 50)
#> Beginning Step 3 of SCALPEL
#> Constructing training and validation sets
#> Fitting SGL on training set
#> Connected component: 1 of 2
#> Connected component: 2 of 2
#> Calculating validation error
#> Fitting SGL
#> Connected component: 1 of 2
#> Connected component: 2 of 2
#> Saving results
#> Step 3 of SCALPEL finished!

By requiring clusters to have 50 elements, we have excluded the second neuron in step3largeCluster$A, which we can see in the plots below.

#plot the dictionary from Step 2, A
plotSpatial(scalpelOutput = step3largeCluster, neuronSet = "A", title = "A")
#plot the filtered dictionary from Step 3, Afilter
plotSpatial(scalpelOutput = step3largeCluster, neuronSet = "Afilter", title = "Afilter")

In addition to filtering components based on their cluster size using minClusterSize, there are a couple other ways columns of A may not be included in Afilter. First, some videos may have noise artifacts on the boundary of the field of view, and thus we may want to remove elements on the boundary. When removeBorder is TRUE, the dictionary elements containing pixels in the 10-pixel border of the video are removed prior to fitting the sparse group lasso. Second, excludeReps can be used to manually exclude dictionary elements from the sparse group lasso for any reason.

In this step, there are two different ways to specify the value of \(\lambda\) to use in the sparse group lasso. You can specify a method for choosing \(\lambda\) via lambdaMethod, or directly choose a value and provide it via lambda. Specifying "trainval" for lambdaMethod means that \(\lambda\) will be chosen using a validation set approach, and specifying "distn" means that \(\lambda\) will be chosen as the negative of the 0.1% quantile of elements of active pixels (i.e., those contained in at least one dictionary element) of the processed data. The value of \(\alpha\) for solving the sparse group lasso is specified using alpha, and has a default value of 0.9.

#we exclude the 4th and 5th dictionary elements, which from our plot above didn't seem to be distinct neurons
#and we choose lambda using the distribution of the processed data
step3out = scalpelStep3(step2Output = step2out, lambdaMethod = "distn", excludeReps = c(4, 5))
#> Beginning Step 3 of SCALPEL
#> Calculating value of lambda to use
#> Fitting SGL
#> Connected component: 1 of 3
#> Connected component: 2 of 3
#> Connected component: 3 of 3
#> Saving results
#> Step 3 of SCALPEL finished!
#we can summarize the results
summary(step3out)
#> Step 3 of SCALPEL
#> 
#> SUMMARY
#> We began with 5 dictionary elements, and 3 of these were included in the sparse group lasso model. The sparse group lasso was fit with lambda=0.04978 and alpha=0.9, and there were 3 neurons with non-zero temporal components (i.e., the neuron was estimated to be active in at least one frame).
#> 
#> ARGUMENTS USED
#> Method to choose lambda: Using distribution of Y
#> User-supplied lambda value: N/A
#> Value of alpha: 0.9
#> Minimum cluster size for dictionary element to be included in the sparse group lasso: 1
#> Should spatial components on the border of the video be included in the sparse group lasso? Yes
#> Indices of dictionary elements to exclude from the sparse group lasso: 4, 5
#alternatively, we can directly specify lambda
step3out_pickLambda = scalpelStep3(step2Output = step2out, lambda = 0.05, excludeReps = c(4, 5))
#> Beginning Step 3 of SCALPEL
#> Fitting SGL
#> Connected component: 1 of 3
#> Connected component: 2 of 3
#> Connected component: 3 of 3
#> Saving results
#> Step 3 of SCALPEL finished!

Plotting Functions

There are five plotting functions that can be used with the output from scalpelStep3(): plotResults(), plotResultsAllLambda(), plotSpatial(), plotTemporal(), and plotBrightest(). These functions plot the spatial and/or temporal components that result from fitting the sparse group lasso. The arguments for the first four of these functions are quite similar. The argument neuronsToDisplay allows you to plot only a subset of the components, with the default being to plot all of them. Only the outline of the spatial components are plotted if border=TRUE, and whether the spatial components are numbered is controlled by number. The colors of the components and the transparency of the spatial components are controlled via colVec and pctTransp (a number between 0 and 1), respectively. Custom titles and axis labels can also be specified when appropriate via various arguments.

#plot the results of only neurons 1 and 3, with no numbering
#use custom colors, custom titles, and only draw the outlines of neurons
plotResults(scalpelOutput = step3out, neuronsToDisplay = c(1, 3), colVec = c("red", "blue", "orange"), number = FALSE, border = TRUE, titleA = "Neurons 1 & 3", titleZ = "Calcium over time", ylabZ = "Neuron")

The functions plotSpatial() and plotTemporal() have similar arguments as plotResults(), but they plot only the spatial components or temporal components, respectively. Note that plotSpatial() can also be used to plot any set of spatial components by specifying A and videoHeight. For example, we can plot the first element in the preliminary spatial component dictionary, saved as miniOut$Azero. Well also use the zoom argument to zoom in.

#plot a zoomed-in view of one of the preliminary dictionary elements
plotSpatial(A = miniOut$Azero, videoHeight = videoHeight, zoom = TRUE, neuronsToDisplay = 1)

If we are interested in using a different value of \(\lambda\), we can review the results for a whole sequence of \(\lambda\) values using plotResultsAllLambda(scalpelOutput = miniOut). The optional arguments for plotResultsAllLambda() are the same as those for plotResults().

As we saw previously, plotBrightest() allows us to visualize the frames estimated to have the highest amounts of fluorescence for each estimated neuron. Here, we demonstrate some of the non-default values for the arguments of plotBrightest().

#non-default values for all arguments:
#plot the third brightest frame ('brightIndex=3') for neuron 2
#using the raw data and only outline that neuron ('neuronsToOutline="main"')
#also use a custom title
plotBrightest(scalpelOutput = miniOut, AfilterIndex = 2, videoType = "raw", neuronsToOutline = "main", brightIndex = 3, title = "Neuron 2")

Revisiting Previously-Run Results

The results from running the SCALPEL pipeline using the single function scalpel() or the individual step functions, scalpelStep0(), scalpelStep1(), scalpelStep2(), and scalpelStep3(), are automatically saved in various sub-directories of the user-specified outputFolder. This is convenient as it allows you to easily return to results run during a previous R session. To pull in old results, we use getScalpel(). The arguments for getScalpel() mimic those used when calling the pipeline functions, with the exception of Step 1. When Step 1 is run, a 5-digit unique identifier is generated for your set of arguments used. Thus to pull in results, we need to know this version number. It is saved as part of the output. For example, the version number for our original run of SCALPEL is given below.

miniOut$version
#> [1] 38137

Well cheat and use miniOut$version to read a copy of the results back into R. However, in practice, youll need to look up version in the saved results on your computer. To do this, look in outputFolder and youll see a folder named Step1_version where version will be a 5-digit number. If youve run Step 1 multiple times, there will be multiple folders like this. To determine which version is the one of interest, review the Step1Summary.txt file in each of the folders. Youll be able to see which version corresponds to the parameters of interest. Note that if youve only run each step a single time, its sufficient to only specify the outputFolder when calling getScalpel().

#retrieve previous results
miniOutCopy = getScalpel(outputFolder = outputFolder, version = miniOut$version)

The object miniOutCopy is exactly the same as miniOut, which resulted from directly running scalpel(). To confirm this, we can use identical().

identical(miniOut, miniOutCopy)
#> [1] TRUE

In this example, we only specified outputFolder, which was the folder in which we asked R to save the results originally, and version, as the rest of the parameters we used were the default values. If we had used non-default values when originally running scalpel(), we would have needed to specify these when calling getScalpel(). For example, we can instead read in the results corresponding to a cutoff of 0.08. Note that we need to specify any parameters for which we used non-default values.

#retrieve results for cutoff=0.08, lambdaMethod="distn", and excluding components 4 and 5
smallerCutoffOut = getScalpel(outputFolder = outputFolder, version = miniOut$version, cutoff = 0.08, lambdaMethod = "distn", excludeReps = c(4, 5))

Youll notice that we used getScalpel() to retrieve the results, even though the individual steps were run using scalpelStep2() and scalpelStep3(). You can use getScalpel() to retrieve the results for the entire pipeline, even if some or all of the steps were run individually.

However, if only some of the steps have been run, getScalpel() will not work as it will fail to find results for all steps. Instead, we can read in the results for individual steps using getScalpelStep0(), getScalpelStep1(), getScalpelStep2(), and getScalpelStep3(). For example, we ran Step 1 again with different size constraints and threshold values, but never ran Steps 2 or 3 on the results. Thus we can read in the results using getScalpelStep1().

step1outCopy = getScalpelStep1(outputFolder = outputFolder, version = step1out$version)
#check that the results are identical
identical(step1out, step1outCopy)
#> [1] TRUE

Note that we once again cheated and used step1out$version for version, even though this wouldnt typically be available as the results are not yet read into R. In practice, youd look in outputFolder for the version number of the Step 1 folder containing the results of interest.

Manual Filtering of Estimated Neurons Between Steps 2 and 3

The set of estimated neurons from Step 2 of SCALPEL can be manually inspected to determine whether they appear to be true neurons. We can perform this manual classification between Steps 2 and 3 by examining the frames of the video from which the spatial component was derived. We then use the manually refined set of neurons in Step 3. We have two options for performing this classification: using an interactive process where the frames are shown in R and youre prompted for the classification, or a non-interactive process where the frames are saved in a folder and you sort the plots according to their classification. We explain these processes below, but also demonstrate them in a video available at ajpete.com/software.

Well begin by discussing the interactive process. For each function we use, there are two arguments: scalpelOutput indicating the analysis of interest, and neuronSet="A" indicating we are reviewing the neurons from Step 2. We first run the reviewNeuronsInteractive() function, which will guide you through classifying each neuron by displaying the frame from which its representative was derived. You can classify each estimated neuron as a true neuron, a false neuron, or undetermined. There is also the option to quit the review process, and resume it later by calling the function again. For estimated neurons of undetermined status, we use the reviewNeuronsMoreFrames() function that saves additional frames from which members of the cluster were derived. The reviewOverlappingNeurons() function is useful in determining whether overlapping estimated neurons come from distinct true neurons. Finally, we can update the classification status of any estimated neuron using the updateNeuronsInteractive() function.

###NOT RUN
###THESE COMMANDS WERE NOT RUN AS PART OF THIS VIGNETTE
###THE FOLLOWING COMMANDS ARE INTERACTIVE
###SEE THE VIDEO AT ajpete.com/software FOR HOW TO USE THESE COMMANDS
#do an initial review of each estimated neuron
reviewNeuronsInteractive(scalpelOutput = miniOut, neuronSet = "A")
#gather more information as to whether an estimated neuron is real
reviewNeuronsMoreFrames(scalpelOutput = miniOut, neuronSet = "A")
reviewOverlappingNeurons(scalpelOutput = miniOut, neuronSet = "A")
#update the status of the neurons we were unsure about
updateNeuronsInteractive(scalpelOutput = miniOut, neuronSet = "A")

Once the dictionary from Step 2 has been manually classified, we can refit Step 3 only using the elements we classified as true neurons. We do this using the excludeReps argument in the scalpelStep3() function. This will exclude any estimated neurons classified as not being neurons. If there are any elements not yet classified or with an undetermined status, these will still be included.

###NOT RUN
###THIS COMMAND WAS NOT RUN AS PART OF THIS VIGNETTE
###SEE THE VIDEO AT ajpete.com/software FOR HOW TO USE THIS COMMAND
step3discarded = scalpelStep3(step2Output = miniOut, excludeReps = "discarded")

As an alternative to the interactive process discussed above, we can use analogous functions to perform the process non-interactively. This is useful for videos with a large number of estimated neurons. We use the function reviewNeurons() initially. Instead of displaying the frames of interest in R, the plots are saved to a specified folder. This folder will include empty directories named keep, discard, and unsure into which you can sort the plots. After completing this sorting, the function updateNeurons() will update the classification based on the folder into which each plot was placed. As in the interactive process, we can use the functions reviewNeuronsMoreFrames() and reviewOverlappingNeurons() to gather additional evidence as to whether an estimated neuron appears to be real. The plots can be moved between the keep, discard, and unsure folders at any time to update their classification, as long as the function updateNeurons() is subsequently run to update the classification status.

###NOT RUN
###THESE COMMANDS WERE NOT RUN AS PART OF THIS VIGNETTE
###THE FOLLOWING COMMANDS ARE INTERACTIVE
###SEE THE VIDEO AT ajpete.com/software FOR HOW TO USE THESE COMMANDS
#save the plots for determining the classifications
reviewNeurons(scalpelOutput = scalpelOutput, neuronSet = "A")
#update the status of the neurons once files are sorted
updateNeurons(scalpelOutput = scalpelOutput, neuronSet = "A")
#gather more information as to whether an estimated neuron is real
reviewNeuronsMoreFrames(scalpelOutput = scalpelOutput, neuronSet = "A")
reviewOverlappingNeurons(scalpelOutput = scalpelOutput, neuronSet = "A")
#update the status of the neurons once files are sorted again
updateNeurons(scalpelOutput = scalpelOutput, neuronSet = "A")

We can compare the refined dictionary prior to manual classification to that after manual classification using the following code.

###NOT RUN
###THESE COMMANDS WERE NOT RUN AS PART OF THIS VIGNETTE
###SEE THE VIDEO AT ajpete.com/software FOR HOW TO USE THESE COMMANDS
#dictionary prior to manual classification
plotSpatial(scalpelOutput = miniOut, neuronSet = "A")
#dictionary after to manual classification
plotSpatial(scalpelOutput = miniOut, neuronSet = "A", neuronsToDisplay = "kept")

The function getNeuronStatus() can be used to load the vector giving the current classification of each estimated neuron.

###NOT RUN
###THIS COMMAND WAS NOT RUN AS PART OF THIS VIGNETTE
###SEE THE VIDEO AT ajpete.com/software FOR HOW TO USE THIS COMMAND
getNeuronStatus(scalpelOutput = miniOut, neuronSet = "A")

Plotting a Custom Set of Neurons

After running all steps of the SCALPEL pipeline, we can manually review each of the final estimated neurons, i.e., those in the filtered dictionary, miniOut$Afilter. The goal of manually reviewing the final set of estimated neurons is to identify whether all of these elements appear to be true neurons. For example, there may be components that appear to be dendrites or noise artifacts.

To perform this classification process, we actually use the same set of functions used to manually classify the estimated neurons from Step 2 in the previous section, except we now use neuronSet="Afilter". We demonstrate this process in a video available at ajpete.com/software.

Once the classification process is finished, we can use our classification to plot the results for only the estimated neurons determined to be true neurons. Note that any estimated neurons that were not classified or had an undetermined status will also be shown in these plots. We can use the classifications in our plotting functions via the argument neuronsToOutline="kept" in plotBrightest() and plotVideoVariance(), and the argument neuronsToDisplay="kept" in plotResults(), plotResultsAllLambda(), plotSpatial(), and plotTemporal().

###NOT RUN
###THESE COMMANDS WERE NOT RUN AS PART OF THIS VIGNETTE
###SEE THE VIDEO AT ajpete.com/software FOR HOW TO USE THESE COMMANDS
#plotting functions that use the neuronsToOutline="kept" argument
plotVideoVariance(scalpelOutput = miniOut, neuronSet = "Afilter", neuronsToOutline = "kept")
plotBrightest(scalpelOutput = miniOut, AfilterIndex = 1, neuronsToOutline = "kept")
#plotting functions that use the neuronsToDisplay="kept" argument
plotResults(scalpelOutput = miniOut, neuronsToDisplay = "kept")
plotResultsAllLambda(scalpelOutput = miniOut, neuronsToDisplay = "kept")
plotSpatial(scalpelOutput = miniOut, neuronSet = "Afilter", neuronsToDisplay = "kept")
plotTemporal(scalpelOutput = miniOut, neuronsToDisplay = "kept")

Alternatively to reviewing the final set of neurons after Step 3, we can perform this classification process between Steps 2 and 3, and then fit the sparse group lasso in Step 3 using only the set of manually selected neurons. This alternative process is discussed in the previous section.

Efficient Plotting Using getY()

The plotting functions plotFrame(), plotThresholdedFrame(), plotVideoVariance(), plotCandidateFrame(), and plotBrightest() use the video data in their plots. Though the video can be automatically read in when these functions are called, there is the option to read the video data into R a single time, and then provide this data to any of these functions. The advantage of this approach is that it avoids repeatedly reading the data into memory, which can be time consuming for larger videos.

To read in either the raw data (saved in rawDataFolder) or the processed data that results from Step 0, use getY(). By default, the processed data is read in.

processedY = getY(scalpelOutput = miniOut)

If you instead want to use the raw data, specify this using the videoType argument.

rawY = getY(scalpelOutput = miniOut, videoType = "raw")

The output from getY() can then be provided as the Y argument in the plotting functions discussed above. The resulting plot will be exactly the same as the default of automatically reading in the data, as we see in the example below, but it is a faster approach if you are calling these functions multiple times.

#video data is automatically read in
plotFrame(scalpelOutput = miniOut, frame = 100, videoType = "processed")

#video data is provided as 'Y' argument
plotFrame(scalpelOutput = miniOut, frame = 100, Y = processedY)

Overview of All Functions

Now that weve introduced all of the functions in the scalpel R package, we can recap how the functions can be used in conjunction with one another. The arrows in the diagram below indicate that the output from one function can be used as input for a different function.

There are four main types of functions in the scalpel R package:

  • Pipeline functions: The SCALPEL pipeline can be run with a single command using scalpel(), or step by step using scalpelStep0(), scalpelStep1(), scalpelStep2(), and scalpelStep3(). Additionally, the output from scalpel() can be provided to scalpelStep1(), scalpelStep2(), and scalpelStep3() to refit the step with different parameters.

  • Refinement functions: These allow you to fine-tune results from the SCALPEL pipeline using manual modification. The function updateThreshold() is an optional step between Steps 0 and 1 to modify the smallest value used for image segmentation in Step 1 on the basis of reviewing some sample thresholded frames. There is also a process for manually classifying the estimated neurons from Step 2 or Step 3 as to whether they appear to be true neurons or not. There is a set of functions to do this interactively (reviewNeuronsInteractive(), updateNeuronsInteractive()) or a set to do this using saved plots (reviewNeurons(), updateNeurons()). The functions reviewNeuronsMoreFrames() and reviewOverlappingNeurons() are also useful in either process. These functions do not return anything, but rather update the classification status of the estimated neurons in a saved file, which can be used in various functions through the arguments neuronsToOutline="kept", neuronsToDisplay="kept", and excludeReps="discarded". This manual classification process of estimated neurons is detailed more in above sections.

  • Reload functions: The functions getScalpel(), getScalpelStep0(), getScalpelStep1(), getScalpelStep2(), and getScalpelStep3() allow you to reload results from a previous session. The function getY() allows you to load the video data, which is helpful when repeatedly calling some of the plotting functions. The function getNeuronStatus() allows you to load the manual neuron classifications made using reviewNeurons() or reviewNeuronsInteractive().

  • Plotting functions: These generally correspond to a single step of the pipeline and can be used on output from that specific step (or a later step) and output from scalpel().

Additionally, summary() can be called on the output from any of the SCALPEL pipeline functions.

The table below indicates the steps of the pipeline from which the output can be used as input for each of the plotting functions. Additionally, output from scalpel() can be used with any of the plotting functions. It also indicates which functions have an argument Y that takes in the output from getY() for increased efficiency in plotting.

Working with Large Videos

There are a couple of options to decrease the computational time needed when working with larger videos. First of all, we recommend breaking the raw data into chunks of approximately 1000 frames and saving them in separate files (Y_1.mat, Y_2.mat, etc.; Y_1.rds, Y_2.rds, etc.; Y_1.txt, Y_2.txt, etc.; or Y_1.txt.gz, Y_2.txt.gz, etc. depending on fileType). By doing this, scalpelStep0() (or scalpel()) can be run with the argument processSeparately=TRUE, which means that the pre-processing will be done separately for each of the files. This avoids reading very large data files into memory in R and reduces the computational time needed.

When using the plotting functions that rely on the raw or processed data (plotFrame(), plotThresholdedFrame(), plotVideoVariance(), plotCandidateFrame(), and plotBrightest()), we previously recommended using getY() to load the video data into R a single time and pass the output into these functions when calling them repeatedly. For large videos, there is the argument part in getY() that allows you to only read in a single chunk of data. For example, we could use Ypart3 = getY(scalpelOutput = scalpelOut, part = 3) if scalpelOutput corresponded to a video with at least three raw data files that were processed separately. Using the argument Y=Ypart3 in the plotting functions will work automatically as described previously, as long as the requested frame is in that chunk of data (i.e., in Ypart3$currentFrames).

Troubleshooting

To access the documentation for a specific function in R, use the command ?function. For example, use ?scalpelStep3 to find out more about the scalpelStep3() function.

Options for Advanced Users

Advanced users may want to make custom plots or investigate the output in a way thats not readily done using the functions in the R package. For those familiar with R, this should be relatively straightforward using the output from the main function scalpel(), or the individual step functions scalpelStep0(), scalpelStep1(), scalpelStep2(), and scalpelStep3(). For a list of the elements in the output object for each of these functions, refer to the R reference manual, which is available https://CRAN.R-project.org/package=scalpel/scalpel.pdf.
